The detailed feature extraction process is shown below. As shown in Fig. 2(a), (b), and (c), the IC curve exhibits significant shifts with continuous discharge cycles. During discharge, the IC curve represents the rate of lithium extraction from the cathode, where each characteristic point reflects a specific electrochemical phase transition or delithiation reaction. During the discharge process, particularly at higher voltage levels (3.0–3.3 V), characteristic changes in the tangent slopes are observed that directly indicate lithium extraction kinetics. Key voltage points with distinct physical significance are identified: 3.3 V (
S
0
) marks the initial delithiation where surface lithium ions begin extraction; 3.23 V (
S
1
) represents the α -phase to intermediate phase transition; 3.18 V (
S
2
) indicates the main two-phase reaction region; 3.16 V (
S
3
) corresponds to maximum phase transformation rate; 3.13 V (
S
4
) reflects the transition to Li-poor phase; and 2.9 V (
S
5
) signifies final extraction stages. The slopes at 3.2 V and 3.0 V (
S
6
) are particularly important as they capture the onset and completion of bulk phase transformation kinetics. The extreme points (
S
7
) and their voltages (
S
8
) represent peak reaction rates during phase transformation, which decrease with active material degradation and surface film formation. The tangential slope before the minimum value (
S
9
) serves as a kinetic limitation indicator developing with aging. The IC curve area where
d Q / d V = − 1
(
S
10
) quantifies the total discharge capacity during main phase transition, providing a direct measure of active material utilization and thus SOH. These features were selected based on their demonstrated sensitivity to various degradation mechanisms affecting capacity fade and resistance increase.
